No, there is no way using the `hasNextLine()` method itself, if that&#39;s what you want.

It is because the scanner doesn&#39;t advance past any input when you call the `hasNextLine()` method, you are simply asking the scanner instance if it has another line in the input of this scanner.

To achieve your intended behaviour, you need to advance the scanner past the current line by calling the `nextLine()` method. You can choose to store the read input or ignore it.

```java
Scanner input = new Scanner(System.in);
System.out.println(&quot;text&quot;);
input.nextLine();
System.out.println(&quot;text&quot;);
input.nextLine();
System.out.println(&quot;text&quot;);
input.nextLine();
System.out.println(&quot;text&quot;);
input.nextLine();
System.out.println(&quot;text&quot;);
```

